On Fri, Jul 29, 2016 at 12:16:14PM +0200,
 Niels ten Oever <niels@article19.org> wrote 
 a message of 219 lines which said:

> > Last important point, when rereading the evaluation of XMPP in
> > 5.2.6, I cannot help thinking it is technically correct but it may
> > make people consider that the XMPP authors were working for the
> > NSA or the FSB, trying very hard to break human rights in the
> > protocol. May be adding something that these evaluations are done
> > on the basis of HR influence, and that the engineers who built
> > these protocols had many other issues, and many trade-offs to
> > consider (in the case of XMPP, the use of the servers, which has a
> > lot of consequences for HR, is because user's machines are not
> > reachable 100 % of the time.)
> 
> Sure! We don't want to lambast XMPP, but simply show how hard it is.
> Would you like to offer text?

A proposal to add at the end of 5.2.2.1 (stored in
<https://github.com/bortzmeyer/IRTF-HRPC/commit/f20144d9a795d617dd6a327fa75779cff8363c41>):

It is important to note that the assessment here is not a general
judgment on these protocols. When they were conceived, there were many
criteria to take into account. For instance, relying on an external
server can be bad for freedom of speech (it creates one more control
point, where censorship could be applied) but it may be a necessity if
the endpoints are not connected and reachable permanently. So, when we
say "protocol X has feature Y, which may endanger the freedom of
speech", it does not mean that protocol X is bad and even less that
its authors were evil. The goal here is to show, with actual examples,
that the design of protocols have practical consequences for some
human rights and these consequences have to be considered at design
time.


