phrased as a question:

>   Question(s): Does your protocol have text strings that are readable
>   or entered by humans?  Does your protocol allow Unicode encoded in
>   UTF-8 only, thereby shifting conversion issues away from individual
>   choices?  Did you have a look at [RFC6365]?

It took me some time to be sure that "allowing Unicode in UTF-8 only"
was regarded as the best practice ("shifting away from individual
choices" seemed a fascist decision at first). Why not rewriting it:

Does your protocol have text strings that are readable or entered by
humans?  Does your protocol allow Unicode encoded in UTF-8 only,
thereby preventing any conversion issues?  If other character sets /
encodings are allowed, does your protocol mandates a proper tagging of
the charset? Did you have a look at [RFC6365]?


