Hi Niels and everyone,

Following the previous discussion I would propose a few changes:



>    Explanation: The Internet was able to developed into the global
>    network of networks because of the existence of open, non-proprietar=
y
>    standards [Zittrain].  They are crucial for enabling
>    interoperability.  Yet, open standards are not explicitly defined
>    within the IETF. =20


This would be considered news to most people at the IETF.  That doesn't
mean the IETF does ALL open standards but all IETF standards are as
close to open as any I know.  Indeed it's not clear that the focus here
should be the IETF, but rather more general.  There are two approaches
you could take to address this issue:

1.  Drop the sentence.  I think that generalizes the point.

2.  Replace the sentence with something more factually grounded, such as
the following:

"Organizations that espouse open standards philosophies may find
themselves entangled through normative references to closed standards or
proprietary approaches."

And then go on from there.


> On the subject, [RFC2606] states: Various national
>    and international standards bodies, such as ANSI, ISO, IEEE, and ITU=
-
>    T, develop a variety of protocol and service specifications that are=

>    similar to Technical Specifications defined at the IETF.  National
>    and international groups also publish "implementors' agreements" tha=
t
>    are analogous to Applicability Statements, capturing a body of
>    implementation-specific detail concerned with the practical
>    application of their standards.  All of these are considered to be
>    "open external standards" for the purposes of the Internet Standards=

>    Process.  Similarly, [RFC3935] does not define open standards but
>    does emphasize the importance of 'open process': any interested
>    person can participate in the work, know what is being decided, and
>    make his or her voice heard on the issue.  Part of this principle is=

>    the IETF's commitment to making its documents, WG mailing lists,
>    attendance lists, and meeting minutes publicly available on the
>    Internet.

Again here you may wish to use the IETF as an examplar, but not make
this about the IETF.  By the way, OpenStand is probably worth considering=
=2E

Finally, I think it's useful to explain some of the complexity around
open standards.  This is not an easy subject.  There was an excellent
article by Steven Levy on the impact of normative references in
code.[1]  Some of us remember Carl Malamud, who used to participate in
the IETF.  This is a great read, and his cause is good.  But the IETF is
in a bit of a privileged spot: ISOC and ICANN foot our bills and those
of the W3C, at least in part.  That helps keep things open.  Other
standards organizations still have to pay the bills.  Some do that by
selling documents, others do it through membership fees as a price of
influence.  Traveling around the world to participate is also
expensive.  And so there are many aspects that limit openness.  At the
same time, openness tends to slow things down.  In a hot market, that's
death to a young company.

I would finally point out that open standards on the web is almost an
oxymoron.  Much of the communication to and from the browser is in
javascript, and apps on your phone are written generally to be
two-sided, such that there is NO standardization.  Should there be?=20
What is the value to society and what human rights are at stake?  This
causes me to think a bit about the hourglass model and how we
standardize at its neck more so than elsewhere.

And this brings me back to an earlier point: if this draft is intended
to inform the discussion, let's insure we have captured these sorts of
complexities.  And then if there are clear recommendations to be made,
let's hear them.


>
>    Open standards are important as they allow for permissionless
>    innovation, which is important to maintain the freedom and ability t=
o
>    freely create and deploy new protocols on top of the communications
>    constructs that currently exist.

While I like a good turn of phrase as much as the next person,  I
suggest that "permissionless innovation" is something of a marketing
term, and it goes undefined within the document.  If you are going to
use it, you should explain what it is and why it is important.

Eliot

