Hi Niels (and sorry for so many "finally"s that were not in fact final ;-=
)

Summary:

I've the same problem as Andrew.  Is your target audience the IETF or
the broader community?  An answer to that question will help us in many
ways.


On 9/20/16 10:29 AM, Niels ten Oever wrote:
> Hi Elliot,
>
> On 09/20/2016 10:05 AM, Eliot Lear wrote:
>> Hi Niels and everyone,
>>
>> Following the previous discussion I would propose a few changes:
>>
>>
>>
>>>    Explanation: The Internet was able to developed into the global
>>>    network of networks because of the existence of open, non-propriet=
ary
>>>    standards [Zittrain].  They are crucial for enabling
>>>    interoperability.  Yet, open standards are not explicitly defined
>>>    within the IETF. =20
>>
>> This would be considered news to most people at the IETF.  That doesn'=
t
>> mean the IETF does ALL open standards but all IETF standards are as
>> close to open as any I know. =20
> This might be a language issue. What is meant is that there is no IETF
> definition for what an 'open standard' is.
>
> Indeed it's not clear that the focus here

Well so this is the issue.  Is this draft intended to address just the
IETF or be more broadly applicable?  If you want it to be more broadly
applicable the trick here is to use the IETF or other SDOs as examples.=20
Remember, we're here in the iRtf and we don't need to focus on the
IETF.  Choose wisely ;-)


>> Again here you may wish to use the IETF as an examplar, but not make
>> this about the IETF.  By the way, OpenStand is probably worth consider=
ing.
>>
>> Finally, I think it's useful to explain some of the complexity around
>> open standards.  This is not an easy subject.  There was an excellent
>> article by Steven Levy on the impact of normative references in
>> code.[1]  Some of us remember Carl Malamud, who used to participate in=

>> the IETF.  This is a great read, and his cause is good.  But the IETF =
is
>> in a bit of a privileged spot: ISOC and ICANN foot our bills and those=

>> of the W3C, at least in part.  That helps keep things open.  Other
>> standards organizations still have to pay the bills.  Some do that by
>> selling documents, others do it through membership fees as a price of
>> influence.  Traveling around the world to participate is also
>> expensive.  And so there are many aspects that limit openness.  At the=

>> same time, openness tends to slow things down.  In a hot market, that'=
s
>> death to a young company.
>>
> Not sure if the ecnomic models of open standards are within the scope o=
f
> this document.

I'm sympathetic to the idea of not wildly expanding the scope of this
document or research group to go beyond human rights.  But I think this
hangs on the notion of whether permissionless innovation is a human
right, and then whether open standards are required for permissionless
innovation.  Carl's work, and the quote from Justice Breyer, get to the
heart of the risks of normative references by laws themselves.  In this
sense, the IETF is just about ideal for a reference, not that most of us
would encourage any such references (what happens if we update an RFC,
for example).  And so again: it depends on your intended purpose.  If it
is to inform society about the relationship between standards and human
rights, the I would say there is a relationship.  If your intent is to
improve IETF processes through an informational document within the
context of the IRTF, then I would say it is possible to scope down.  But
that does limit the applicability of your work.  Again, choose wisely.


>> I would finally point out that open standards on the web is almost an
>> oxymoron.  Much of the communication to and from the browser is in
>> javascript, and apps on your phone are written generally to be
>> two-sided, such that there is NO standardization.  Should there be?=20
>> What is the value to society and what human rights are at stake? =20
> I am not sure whether web standards fall within the scope of this draft=
=2E

See above.  If you are strictly focused on the IETF, I guess you're
right, but I would claim that then this is a missed opportunity.
>
>> This
>> causes me to think a bit about the hourglass model and how we
>> standardize at its neck more so than elsewhere.
>>
>> And this brings me back to an earlier point: if this draft is intended=

>> to inform the discussion, let's insure we have captured these sorts of=

>> complexities.  And then if there are clear recommendations to be made,=

>> let's hear them.
>>
>>
> I think starting of with documenting the issues is already a great step=
,
> actually.

Ok.  How much depends on the answer to the question at the top of this
email, right?

>
>>>    Open standards are important as they allow for permissionless
>>>    innovation, which is important to maintain the freedom and ability=
 to
>>>    freely create and deploy new protocols on top of the communication=
s
>>>    constructs that currently exist.
>> While I like a good turn of phrase as much as the next person,  I
>> suggest that "permissionless innovation" is something of a marketing
>> term, and it goes undefined within the document.  If you are going to
>> use it, you should explain what it is and why it is important.
>>
> We could add this definition to the glossary:
>
> "Permissionless innovation," is the freedom to explore new technologies=

> or businesses without seeking prior approval.
>
> from: Thierer, A. Permissionless Innovation: The Continuing Case for
> Comprehensive Technological Freedom. Mercatus Center at George Mason
> University, 2014.
>

That is as good as any, but then I would say there should be some
discussion as to its relationship to human rights.  And that in itself
will also inform you as to how much of the open standards discussion
should be captured.

Eliot


--HKeKDnFCw66fDX09OAHtido6no9TioxU4--

